A code-level study of how the same UI component — the product card — is shared across multiple applications in two different frameworks, using the ecommerce Angular storefront and the Symbols storefront.

Findings: At component scale, a shared product card costs 13 files / ~1,600 lines in Angular versus one shared file and a 3–4 line override in Symbols. At page scale the gap widens: the product-details page is forked into ~3,400 lines of duplicated view across the two Angular apps, while Symbols keeps one shared page and swaps a single child component. The difference is structural, not stylistic.
Executive Summary
— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
Both storefronts ship the same feature set across multiple apps that share a common look. The product card is the ideal test case: it appears on listings, product detail, wishlist and search, and it differs slightly between the consumer app and the voucher app (the voucher app has no “add to basket” button). How each framework expresses “the same card, minus one button” exposes its real reuse model.
THE CORE DIFFERENCE: In Angular the shared library can only hold the card’s TypeScript logic; its markup (HTML) and styles (SCSS) are copied into each app and have already drifted apart. In Symbols the entire card — structure, style and behaviour — lives in one declarative object in the shared default project, and each app inherits it with a one-line extends.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

How Each Framework Shares the Card
— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
Press enter or click to view image in full size

WHY THIS MATTERS: The unit of reuse in Angular is code behind the view; the view itself is not reusable without extra layers (content projection, shared sub-components, or directives). The unit of reuse in Symbols is the whole component as data, so structure and style travel with the logic by default.
Evidence — The Symbols Card
— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
The shared definition lives once, in default . Abbreviated to show shape (the real file is 388 lines and includes the image, badges, title, price block with full schema.org microdata, free-shipping row and the basket button):
export const ProductCardBase = {
extends: 'Link',
href: (el, s) => '/p/' + (s.slug || s.id || ''),
flow: 'y', background: 'white', borderRadius: 'A2', /* …layout… */
WishlistBtn: { /* heart toggle, login-gated */ },
BadgesContainer:{ /* sale + "new" badges */ },
ImageContainer: { ProductImage: { /* lazy img, hover zoom */ } },
CardBody: {
ProductTitle: { /* h3, itemprop=name */ },
BrandName: { /* … */ },
PriceRow: { OriginalPrice: {…}, CurrentPrice: { /* + schema.org/Offer */ } },
FreeShippingRow: { /* truck icon + label */ }
},
AddToBasketBtn: { // ← the button the voucher app must drop
onClick: async (ev, el, s) => { ev.preventDefault(); await el.call('addToBasket', {…}) }
},
HiddenMicrodata: { /* brand, sku, mpn, seller, category … */ }
}
export const ProductCard = { extends: 'ProductCardBase' }Each app then reuses it. These are the complete per-app files:
export const ProductCard = {
extends: 'ProductCardBase'
}export const ProductCard = {
extends: 'ProductCardBase',
AddToBasketBtn: null // remove the button
}
THE DECISIVE LINE: The voucher app’s entire divergence from the main app is AddToBasketBtn: null . Setting one named node to null removes the basket button while every other part of the card — markup, styling, behaviour, SEO — stays inherited and stays in sync automatically
Evidence — The Angular Card
— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
SHARED BASE CLASS — LOGIC ONLY, NO VIEW
@Component({ selector: 'lib-ui-template-product-card', template: '' }) // ← no markup
export abstract class BaseProductCardComponent implements OnInit {
@Input() product!: ProductListViewModel; /* …inputs… */
addToBasket() { /* … */ }
addToWish() { /* … */ }
getRegularPriceStyles() { /* … */ }
}WHAT EVERY APP MUST ADD ON TOP OF IT
Because the base class has no template, each app re-supplies the view and the wiring. Below are the six files b2c-voucher needs (b2cfrontend has the same six):
// 1. product-card.component.ts — subclass that only points at its own template
@Component({ templateUrl: './product-card.component.html', styleUrls: ['./…scss'] })
export class ProductCardComponent extends BaseProductCardComponent {}
// 2. product-card.component.html → 150 lines of markup (b2c-frontend: 172 lines)
// 3. product-card.component.scss → 437 lines of styles (b2c-frontend: 561 lines)
// 4. product-card.module.ts — NgModule declaring the component
// 5. product-card-wrapper.component.ts — re-declares every @Input/@Output to pass through
// 6. product-card-wrapper.module.ts — a second NgModule wrapping the firstTHE HIDDEN COST: THE VIEW IS DUPLICATED, NOT SHARED: The card’s HTML and SCSS are not in the shared library — they are copied into each app and have already diverged. A diff of the two apps’ templates shows they share almost no lines: different class names (product-card vs voucher-card), different DOM order, different responsive rules.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Totals: 13 files and ~1,612 lines of code across the two apps plus the shared base, for a single logical component.The Change Scenario
— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
The real test of reusability is not building the component once — it is changing it later. Two representative tasks:
Task A — Restyle the card for both apps (e.g. new border radius & price colour)
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Task B — The voucher app should not show the basket button
Press enter or click to view image in full size

OBSERVATION: Angular does have a real shared layer — the base class proves the team invested in reuse. But the framework’s component model keeps view and logic in separate units, so the most-changed part of a card (its markup and styles) is exactly the part that could not be shared without additional scaffolding.
Scaling Up: Page & Module Reuse
— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
The same question applies to whole pages. Both storefronts run multiple apps over one design, so the interesting cases are the pages that differ between apps: the account area, the products listing, the product-details page, and the third step of checkout. Here is how each framework shares — or forks — each one.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

THE PATTERN THAT DECIDES EVERYTHING: In Symbols a page references its parts by name — PurchasePanel: {} , ThirdStep: {} — and the framework resolves the component from the app’s registry. So the page is written once in default ; an app changes the page by defining a component of the same name. Angular has no equivalent “resolve a node by name per app,” so each page must either be parameterised (inputs / injected components) or forked. Account and products listing took the parameterised path; product-details was forked.
Evidence — Page-Level Differences
— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
Symbols · checkout third step — a one-property change
Both apps import the same checkout.js . It references the step by name:
... ThirdStep: {}, // resolves the "ThirdStep" component from this app's registryThe shared component defines a VoucherSection . The voucher app removes it — whole file:
export const ThirdStepBase = {
/* …summary, address,
VoucherSection {…}, ← apply-code box pay button… */
}export const ThirdStep = {
extends: 'ThirdStepBase'
}
export const ThirdStep = {
extends: 'ThirdStepBase',
VoucherSection: null // drop the section
}
Symbols · product details — a focused component swap
The 805-line productDetails.js page (breadcrumbs, gallery, specs, reviews, similar & bonus products) is shared verbatim. It hosts the buy box by name — PurchasePanel: {} — so the voucher app only supplies a 117-line PurchasePanel with its format/giftmessage options. Nothing else on the page is touched, and ipsilon keeps the default panel.
NET PER-APP COST IN SYMBOLS: Voucher’s entire divergence across product-details + checkout is one 117-line component and a 4-line override. The two apps’ full route maps differ by just two lines.
Angular · product details — a forked page
Logic is shared through BaseProductDetailsComponent ( template:’’ , 295 lines), but the view is not. Each app re-supplies a subclass that re-passes every constructor dependency, plus its own template and styles:
// subclass: re-declares 11 injected services just to call super(...)
export class ProductDetailsComponent extends BaseProductDetailsComponent { … }
// product-details.component.html b2c-frontend 379 lines · b2c-voucher 376 lines (77 in common)
// product-details.component.scss b2c-frontend 954 lines · b2c-voucher 1,669 linesTHE DRIFT, QUANTIFIED: The two product-details templates share only 77 of ~379 lines, and their stylesheets have grown to 954 vs 1,669 lines. The voucher-specific buy options are an override addItemToBasket() in the subclass plus bespoke markup — there is no way to inherit the page and replace only the buy box, so the whole view was copied and has since diverged. A layout change now means editing both apps and reconciling two different stylesheets.
The Unified Syntax — One Object vs Three Files
— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
Everything above is possible because of one deeper idea. In Symbols a UI element’s structure, styling and behaviour are one JavaScript object. In Angular the same element is split across three files — an HTML template, an SCSS stylesheet, and a TypeScript class — stitched together by class-name strings and a template micro-language. The unification is what makes components inheritable data; it also means far less code for the same result.
The same element: the “add to basket” button
SYMBOLS — ONE OBJECT NODE
AddToBasketBtn: {
position: 'absolute',
bottom: 'A',
right: 'A',
width: 'B1',
height: 'B1',
borderRadius: '50%',
background: 'primary',
display: 'flex',
align: 'center',
justifyContent: 'center',
cursor: 'pointer',
boxShadow: '0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.18)',
':hover': {
transform: 'scale(1.1)',
boxShadow: '0 4px 14px rgba(0,0,0,0.25)'
},
Icon: {
icon: 'cartAdd',
width: 'A2',
height: 'A2',
color: 'white'
}, // child element
onClick: async (ev, el, s) => { // behaviour
ev.preventDefault(); ev.stopPropagation()
await el.call('addToBasket', { productId: s.id, price: s.price, quantity: 1, … })
}
}Structure (a div), its full styling incl. :hover , a child icon, and the click handler — co-located, in one file, with no class name anywhere. Tokens like ‘A’ , ‘B1’ , ‘primary’ come from the same design system, in the same syntax.
ANGULAR — THREE FILES, GLUED BY CLASS-NAME STRINGS
@if (showAddToBasket && product.availability !== '0' && !useCheckbox) {
<div class="add-to-basket-button" (click)="addToBasket()">
<img class="basket-img" src="…/add-to-cart.svg" />
<span class="basket-hover-box">Dodaj u korpu</span>
</div>
